  "body": " Exam 1 - Math 122    You will solve each of the following problems, making sure to justify them with explanation and supporting computations. Keep the following in mind.   On all problems, you must show all work necessary to justify your solution.    On all problems, you must find a way to explain your reasoning. You must do this in complete sentences.         (25 pts.) Suppose we have a tank that is a perfect sphere with radius 6 feet. The tank is initially empty, but then a spigot is turned on that is pumping water into the tank in a very special way. The faucet is regulated so that the depth of water in the tank is increasing at a constant rate of 0.4 feet per minute.  Let denote the total volume of water (in cubic feet) in the tank at any time (in minutes), and the depth of the water (in feet) at given time . Note that the volume of a sphere is , where is the radius of the sphere.   (4 pts.) How long does it take the tank to fill? What will the values of and be at the moment the tank is full? Explain your reasoning and show work.    (10 pts.) Sketch (by hand) possible graphs of how and change in tandem and how and change in tandem. You may use the graphs below to sketch your graph, or you may use the blank paper provided. In either case, explain why your graphs look the way they do. Also, label any ordered pairs that you know for certain are on the graph.                        (11 pts.) How do your responses change if the tank stays the same but instead the tank is initially full and the tank drains in such a way that the height of the water is always decreasing at a constant rate of 0.25 feet per minute? Make sure you show how long it takes for the tank to drain, draw the graphs for height and volume, and label any ordered pairs that you know for certain are on the graphs. Use the graphs on the next page or sketch your graphs on the blank paper.         (25 pts.) A person is taking a walk along a straight path. Their velocity (in feet per second), which is a function of time (in seconds), is given by the graph below.     f(x)=4*x  g(x)=4  h(x)=-4*(x-4)  k(x)=0  m(x)=6*(x-5)  n(x)=6  p(x)=-6*(x-9)           v=f(t)         (4 pts.) What is the person's velocity when ? when ? Explain how you got your answer from the graph.    (11 pts.) Are there any times when the person's velocity is exactly feet per second? If yes, identify all such times; if not, explain why. Make sure to explain how you get your times from the graph.    (4 pts.) Describe the person's behavior on the time interval . Explain how you got your answer from the graph.    (6 pts.) On which time interval does the person travel a farther distance: or ? Explain your answer, and show any necessary work.         (25 pts.) A cold can of soda is removed from a refrigerator. Its temperature in degrees Fahrenheit is measured at 5-minute intervals, as recorded in the following table.    (minutes)  0  5  10  15  20  25  30  35    Distance (feet)  37.00  44.74  50.77  55.47  59.12  61.97  64.19  65.92       (6 pts.) Determine the average rate of change between and . Show work and include the appropriate units.    (5 pts.) Write a careful sentence to describe the meaning of the number you got in (a) above. Your sentence might look something like On the interval ..., the temperature of the soda is ... on average by ... for each 1-unit increase in ... .    (4 pts.) On which interval is there more total change in the soda's temperature: or ?    (10 pts.) Use an appropriate average rate of change to estimate the soda's temperature when minutes. Explain why you chose that average rate of change and show all supporting work.         (25 pts.) An inverted conical tank with depth 4 feet and radius 2 feet is completely full of water. The tank is being drained by a pump in such a way that the amount of water in the tank is decreasing at a constant rate of 1.5 cubic feet per minute. Let denote the volume of water in the tank at time and the depth of the water in the tank at time , where is measured in minutes. Note that the volume of a cone is , where is the radius of the cone and is the height of the cone.    A cone of radius 2 and height 4. It has water in it that is radius and height .       (2 pts.) How much water is in the tank at when the tank is completely full?    (4 pts.) Explain why volume, , when viewed as a function of time, , is a linear function.    (5 pts.) Determine a formula for . Explain your reasoning and\/or show all necessary work.    (6 pts.) At what exact time will the tank be empty? Explain your reasoning and show work.    (8 pts.) What is a reasonable domain to use for the model ? What is its corresponding range? Explain how you determined your domain and range.       "
