  "title": "Homework Assignment #4 - Math 122",
  "body": " Homework Assignment #4 - Math 122    Due Sunday, 10\/11   These are the requirements for all homework assignments.   On all problems, you must show all work necessary to justify your solution.    On all problems, you must find a way to explain your reasoning. You must do this in complete sentences.    In your explanations and supporting work, do your best to demonstrate your understanding of the problem and the concepts used to solve them.    Make sure you carefully check the accuracy of your computations.   You may turn in your assignment as a hard copy in class, or you may submit your assignment electronically on Blackboard. If you turn in your assignment electronically, you must convert it to a PDF file .   Here are the problems for this assignment. You can find them at the end of Section 1.5 of our textbook. You may use the PDF version of the book, which can be found on Blackboard under Course Information & Resources , or you may use the online version by clicking on on this link and scrolling down to the bottom of the page.    Section 1.5 (pp. 59-60 in the PDF file; at the end of the section in the HTML version)   (28 pts.) Do problem #6. In finding the equations for the functions in parts (a) and (b), only use the red dots given in the graph. In particular, for (b) you may not use the vertex.    (23 pts.) Do problem #8. A couple notes.   You will need the height formula from subsection 1.5.3 (Modeling falling objects), where is the initial velocity and is the initial height. Do not use calculus to solve any of this problem.    Even though part (d) is the last part of the problem, I suggest either doing it first or right after you do part (a).    Do not assume each story of the building has the same height. That will lead you to an incorrect answer.            Collaboration Reflection (5 pts.): For each of the following, write a 2-4 sentence reflection related to your collaboration with your group. You may write about positive contributions made and\/or ways that contributions could be improved.   Write a reflection on your contributions to the collaboration.    Write a reflection about your fellow collaborators' contributions.   You will not be penalized for any shortcomings you or your fellow group members had in your collaboration. Any good-faith effort you make to think about and explain your collaboration experience will be rewarded. I also will not share your reflections with anyone else in your group or the rest of the class without your permission.    If you want to read about some different ways of being a good collaborator, click on this rubric for some ideas. I will not be grading you according to how well you do on this rubric, only on how you reflect about your collaboration.  "
