  "id": "prep-9-18",
  "level": "1",
  "url": "prep-9-18.html",
  "type": "Section",
  "number": "",
  "title": "Resources for 9\/18",
  "body": " Resources for 9\/18    For the content of this class, you will be expected to be able to do the following:     For an applied problem involving a linear function, use your understanding of linear functions to interpret the function and make predictions.      Video & Activities for Applying Linear Functions  Below is a YouTube video on . It is followed by a link to a set of activities that we will be working on in class. Please watch the video and do as many of the activities as you can before class.    Applying Linear Functions  Jojo is now selling commemorative plates. Jojo's marketing analyst says that if Jojo sells the plates for $5 each, they can sell 200 plates, and if Jojo sells the plates for $20 each, they can sell 110 plates. Suppose that if Jojo sells the plates at $p per plate, the amount sold is .     What are and ?    Suppose that the function is a linear function of . What is the slope of ? Include the units.    What does the number you found in #2 tell us about what will happen if Jojo increases the price of the plates? Or decreases the price of the plates?    Find a formula for .    How many plates will Jojo sell if the price is $10?      Feel free to post any questions you have on the FigJam board for the next class.    Video & Activities for Quadratic Equations  Below is a YouTube video reviewing solving quadratic equations . It is followed by a link to a set of activities that we will be working on in class. Please watch the video and do as many of the activities as you can before class.    Quadratic Equations (Not on Quiz)  The following problems are meant to be a review of solving quadratic equations.                         Suppose you are fencing in a rectangular region of area 100 square feet. If the length is 21 feet longer than the width, find the dimensions of the fencing.              You stand on a ledge 10 ft above the ground and throw a ball up in the air. The height of the ball at time seconds is feet. At what time does the ball hit the ground?      Feel free to post any questions you have on the FigJam board for the next class.    Optional Reading  Section 1.4: pp. 38-45  Here is a link for the HTML version of Section 1.4 .  Section 1.5: pp. 51-58  Here is a link for the HTML version of Section 1.5 .   "
