  "body": " Resources for 9\/21    For the content of this class, you will be expected to be able to do the following:     Recognize a quadratic function in both standard form and vertex form.    Given three points on the graph of a quadratic function, determine the system of equations necessary to find the formula for the quadratic function.      Video & Activities for Quadratic Equations  Below is a YouTube video reviewing solving quadratic equations . It is followed by a link to a set of activities that we will be working on in class. Please watch the video and do as many of the activities as you can before class.    Quadratic Equations (Not on Quiz)  The following problems are meant to be a review of solving quadratic equations.                         Suppose you are fencing in a rectangular region of area 100 square feet. If the length is 21 feet longer than the width, find the dimensions of the fencing.              You stand on a ledge 10 ft above the ground and throw a ball up in the air. The height of the ball at time seconds is feet. At what time does the ball hit the ground?      Feel free to post any questions you have on the FigJam board for the next class.    Video & Activities for Introduction to Quadratic Functions  Below is a YouTube video introducing quadratic functions . It is followed by a link to a set of activities that we will be working on in class. Please watch the video and do as many of the activities as you can before class.    Introduction to Quadratic Functions  Each of the following has three points from the graph of a quadratic function. For each problem, do the following.   Determine if the graph opens up or down.    Guess how many -intercepts the graph has.    Write the system of equations you would have to solve to write the quadratic function in the form .        First graph     f(x)=(-3\/8)*(x-3)^2+(27\/8)  g(x)=(3\/16)*(x-6)^2+2.25      (1,4)    (3,2)    (7,10)         Second graph     f(x)=(-3\/8)*(x-3)^2+(27\/8)  g(x)=(3\/16)*(x-6)^2+2.25      (-3,-3)    (-2,3)    (2,-13)         Third graph     f(x)=(-3\/8)*(x-3)^2+(27\/8)  g(x)=(3\/16)*(x-6)^2+2.25      (1,0)    (2,2)    (4,3)         Fourth graph     f(x)=(-3\/8)*(x-3)^2+(27\/8)  g(x)=(3\/16)*(x-6)^2+2.25      (1,2)    (2,3)    (3,4)           Feel free to post any questions you have on the FigJam board for the next class.    Optional Reading  Section 1.5: pp. 51-58  Here is a link for the HTML version of Section 1.5 .   "
