  "title": "Resources for 10\/9",
  "body": " Resources for 10\/9    For the content of this class, you will be expected to be able to do the following:     Solve application problems where functions are created by adding, subtracting, multiplying, and dividing other functions.    Determine the formulas and input values for a piecewise defined function, given appropriate information about the function.    Sketch the graph of a piecewise defined function.      Video & Activities for Applications of Combining Functions (Continued from Last Class)  Below is a YouTube video on combining functions in applications . It is followed by a link to a set of activities that we will be working on in class. Please watch the video and do as many of the activities as you can before class.    Combining Functions (Applications)  Create the following functions and solve the application problems.     Jojo is selling fancy chairs. If the price is dollars, Jojo can sell units.   If Jojo sells their chairs for , what is the total revenue that Jojo takes in? Do the same for and .    Use the same reasoning as in (a) to find a formula for Jojo's total revenue when the price is . We will call the total revenue .    What are the domain and range of ?       You are building a rectangular fenced-in space for your dog right next to your home with 100 feet of fencing. One of the sides of the area is the side of your home.   If is the length of one of the sides of the fence that is attached to your home, and if is the length of the side not attached to your home, what is the area of the fenced-in space?    If the length of one of the sides of the fence that is attached to your home is , what is the area of the fenced-in space? Hint: Let be the length of the side not attached to your home, and solve for in terms of .    If the length of the side of the fence not touching your home is , what is the area of the fenced in space?    What are the domain and range of the above functions?         Feel free to post any questions you have on the FigJam board for the next class.    Video & Activities for Piecewise Defined Functions  Below is a YouTube video on piecewise defined functions . It is followed by a link to a set of activities that we will be working on in class. Please watch the video and do as many of the activities as you can before class.    Piecewise Defined Functions  Consider the functions below. The middle part of the second graph is a parabola.      f(x)= -2*(x+4)+1  g(x)=(1\/3)*(x-4)+1       (-4,1)    (-2,-3)    (-2,-1)    (4,1)          f(x)= -3*(x+3)+4  g(x)=-1.5*(x-1)^2+4  h(x)= 0.5*(x-5)+4        (-3,4)    (-1,-2)    (1,4)    (2,2.5)    (5,4)           Determine the formula(s) for each function above. For the parabola, I suggest using the vertex form of the formula.    Consider the following piecewise defined function.    Compute , , and .    Sketch a graph of .         Feel free to post any questions you have on the FigJam board for the next class.    Optional Reading  Section 1.9: pp. 99-104  Here is a link for the HTML version of Section 1.9 .   "
