  "title": "Resources for 10\/16",
  "body": " Resources for 10\/16    For the content of this class, you will be expected to be able to do the following:     Use your understanding of exponential functions to solve application problems (e.g. interest rate [including compound interest] & radioactive decay).    Describe the end behavior of the function for different values of (i.e. what happens to the function as or ).    Explain why a vertical translation (and perhaps reflection) of an exponential function is appropriate for the temperature of an object over time.    Given appropriate information about the temperature of an object and its environment, construct the formula for a function that models the temperature of the object.      Video & Activities for Applications of Exponential Functions (Continued from Last Class)  Below is a YouTube video on applications for exponential functions . It is followed by a link to a set of activities that we will be working on in class. Please watch the video and do as many of the activities as you can before class.    Exponential Applications  Solve the following application problems.     Suppose we invest money in an account with a fixed annual interest rate. After two years, we have $250 and after five years we have $400.   Find a formula for the amount that is in the account after years.    What is the interest rate on the account?    How much money did we start out with?       Suppose we own something that loses a fixed percentage of its value each year. After 3 years, it is worth $300, and after 7 years, it is worth $200.   Find a formula for the value that the item is worth after years.    What is the annual percentage that the value drops?    What was it worth at the beginning?         Feel free to post any questions you have on the FigJam board for the next class.    Video & Activities for End Behavior of Exponential Functions  Below is a YouTube video on end behavior of exponential functions to help you understand the temperature models in the activities for the next video. It is followed by a link to a set of activities that we will be working on in class. Please watch the video and do as many of the activities as you can before class.    End Behavior of Exponential Functions (Not on Quiz)  These problems are to help you understand the end behavior of exponential functions.     Let .   Look at , , , , and . What is happening to the outputs of the function as the inputs get bigger?    What happens to as gets really big?    What happens to as gets really negative?       Let .   Look at , , , , and . What is happening to the outputs of the function as the inputs get bigger?    What happens to as gets really big?    What happens to as gets really negative?       Let . What happens to as gets really big or really negative? Your answers will depend on the values of and .    Suppose we want to use the function to model a phenomenon, but we need a function that gets close to 20 as gets really big. How can we adjust to make this happen?      Feel free to post any questions you have on the FigJam board for the next class.    Video & Activities for Modeling Temperature with Exponential Functions  Below is a YouTube video on using exponential functions to model temperature . It is followed by a link to a set of activities that we will be working on in class. Please watch the video and do as many of the activities as you can before class.    Modeling Temperature with Exponential Functions  Solve the following temperature problems.     You bring a cup of cold water into a room. Initially, the water is . After 5 minutes, the water is .   If is the temperature of the water at time , find a formula for . Use the model for appropriate constants , , and . Hint: Determine first.    What will the temperature of the water be after 10 minutes?       After dinner, you put your leftovers in the refrigerator, which is . Before you store the food in the refrigerator, it is room temperature, which is . After 30 minutes, the food temperature is down to .   If is the temperature of the leftovers at time , find a formula for .    What will the temperature of the leftovers be after 75 minutes?         Feel free to post any questions you have on the FigJam board for the next class.    Optional Reading  Section 3.1: pp. 153-160  Here is a link for the HTML version of Section 3.1 .  Section 3.2: pp. 165-173  Here is a link for the HTML version of Section 3.2 .   "
