  "title": "Resources for 11\/23",
  "body": " Resources for 11\/23    For the content of this class, you will be expected to be able to do the following:     Identify all -intercepts of the graph of a polynomial expressed in factored form.    Use the factored form of a polynomial to determine how the graph of the function behaves around the -intercepts of the graph of the polynomial (i.e. does the graph touch the -axis or cross the -axis).    Given the graph of a polynomial function, derive a plausible formula for the function.      Video & Activities for Using Sliders in Desmos (Continued from Last Class)  Below is a YouTube video on using sliders in Desmos to help us understand roots of polynomials. It is followed by a link to a set of activities that we will be working on in class. Please watch the video and do as many of the activities as you can before class.    Exploring Polynomial Roots and Graphs (Not on Quiz)  Plug the following functions into Desmos, making a slider for each coefficient (i.e. , , , etc). Play with different values of the coefficients to see the minimum and maximum number of -intercepts of the function (i.e. values of where the function has an output of 0).      ,      ,      ,      ,       Feel free to post any questions you have on the FigJam board for the next class.    Video & Activities for Graphing Polynomials from Roots  Below is a YouTube video on using the roots of polynomials to sketch their graphs . It is followed by a link to a set of activities that we will be working on in class. Please watch the video and do as many of the activities as you can before class.    Graphing Polynomials from Roots  Solve the following problems on the graphs of polynomial functions.     Let . Factor and use this to sketch a graph of .    Let . Use the roots of along with the coefficient to sketch the graph of .    Let with and . Sketch the graph of .    Give a possible formula for the function whose graph is the following.     f(x)=0.2*(x+1)*(x-3)*(x-5)                  Feel free to post any questions you have on the FigJam board for the next class.    Optional Reading  Section 5.2: pp. 262-271  Here is a link for the HTML version of Section 5.2 .   "
